    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Pleas in the Park</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Karen DeCrow letter on June 22 article recalls public indifference to police failure to respond to attacks on other minorities until police failed to respond to reports of middle-class white women being attacked in Central Park</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>With regard to the accounts of women being beaten and robbed in Central Park (news article, June 22), then reporting it to the police and being ignored:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>With regard to the accounts of women being beaten and robbed in Central Park (news article, June 22), then reporting it to the police and being ignored:</p>
        <p>It seems that when blacks were beaten up for driving a decent car or perhaps for just walking on the street, and public authorities ignored their pleas, the rest of us ignored them. After all, we weren't black.</p>
        <p>When gays and lesbians were beaten up for dancing together or maybe for just walking on the street, and public authorities ignored their pleas, the rest of us ignored them. After all, we weren't homosexual.</p>
        <p>Recently, middle-class white women were beaten up while strolling in the park in broad daylight and public authorities ignored their pleas.</p>
        <p>Be careful. It's getting closer.</p>
        <p>KAREN DE CROW  Jamesville, N.Y., June 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
